* Replace flushDiscreteUpdates with flushSync

flushDiscreteUpdates is almost the same as flushSync. It forces passive
effects to fire, because of an outdated heuristic, which isn't ideal but
not that important.

Besides that, the only remaining difference between flushDiscreteUpdates
and flushSync is that flushDiscreteUpdates does not warn if you call it
from inside an effect/lifecycle. This is because it might get triggered
by a nested event dispatch, like `el.focus()`.

So I added a new method, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering, which
is used for the public flushSync API. It includes the warning. And I
removed the warning from flushSync, so the event system can call that
one. In production, flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering gets inlined
to flushSync, so the behavior is identical.

Another way of thinking about this PR is that I renamed flushSync to
flushSyncWithWarningIfAlreadyRendering and flushDiscreteUpdates to
flushSync (and fixed the passive effects thing). The point is to prevent
these from subtly diverging in the future.

* Invert so the one with the warning is the default one

To make Seb happy","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryo4004/react/commits/32eefcb3c5131f4d77a2195ff11a00a2513cf62f"},{"sha":"ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Replace unbatchedUpdates with flushSync (#21776)

There's a weird quirk leftover from the old Stack (pre-Fiber)
implementation where the initial mount of a leagcy (ReactDOM.render)
root is flushed synchronously even inside `batchedUpdates`.

The original workaround for this was an internal method called
`unbatchedUpdates`. We've since added another API that works almost the
same way, `flushSync`.

The only difference is that `unbatchedUpdates` would not cause other
pending updates to flush too, only the newly mounted root. `flushSync`
flushes all pending sync work across all roots. This was to preserve
the exact behavior of the Stack implementation.

But since it's close enough, let's just use `flushSync`. It's unlikely
anyone's app accidentally relies on this subtle difference, and the
legacy API is deprecated in 18, anyway.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryo4004/react/commits/ed6c091fe961a3b95e956ebcefe8f152177b1fb7"},{"sha":"9c7f29ebe75a7546e59038123d3b0c3515bec916","author":{"name":"Moti Zilberman","email":"8b603b22c9c89c36ffb170e88372622acf1aa8d8@gmail.com"},"message":"[WIP] DevTools: Support named hooks for >1 module in a bundle (#21790)

Signed-off-by: Ziheng Liu <lzhfromustc@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/olljanat/moby/commits/5ffcd162b5242df1937c1e03e22232713e605731"},{"sha":"7c97896747726554165480d102d9e46c54334cba","author":{"name":"Steffen Butzer","email":"46adcc64d578e77abc0454761760af40d6d6f8c9@outlook.com"},"message":"libnetwork: processEndpointDelete: Fix deadlock between getSvcRecords and processEndpointDelete

We had some hosts with quite a bit of cycling containers that ocassionally causes docker daemons to lock up.
Most prominently `docker run` commands do not respond and nothing happens anymore.

Looking at the stack trace the following is at least likely sometimes a cause to that:
Two goroutines g0 and g1 can race against each other:
* (g0) 1. getSvcRecords is called and calls (*network).Lock()
       --> Network is locked.
* (g1) 2. processEndpointDelete is called, and calls (*controller).Lock()
       --> Controller is locked
* (g1) 3. processEndpointDelete tries (*network).ID() which calls (*network).Lock().

Signed-off-by: Ziheng Liu <lzhfromustc@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/olljanat/moby/commits/5ffcd162b5242df1937c1e03e22232713e605731"},{"sha":"7c97896747726554165480d102d9e46c54334cba","author":{"name":"Steffen Butzer","email":"46adcc64d578e77abc0454761760af40d6d6f8c9@outlook.com"},"message":"libnetwork: processEndpointDelete: Fix deadlock between getSvcRecords and processEndpointDelete

We had some hosts with quite a bit of cycling containers that ocassionally causes docker daemons to lock up.
Most prominently `docker run` commands do not respond and nothing happens anymore.

Looking at the stack trace the following is at least likely sometimes a cause to that:
Two goroutines g0 and g1 can race against each other:
* (g0) 1. getSvcRecords is called and calls (*network).Lock()
       --> Network is locked.
* (g1) 2. processEndpointDelete is called, and calls (*controller).Lock()
       --> Controller is locked
* (g1) 3. processEndpointDelete tries (*network).ID() which calls (*network).Lock().
* (g0) 4. getSvcRecords calls (*controller).Lock().

3./4. are deadlocked against each other since the other goroutine holds the lock they need.

References https://github.com/moby/libnetwork/blob/b5dc37037049d9b9ef68a3c4611e5eb1b35dd2af/network.go

generated in a different order which was confusing to the user.

Fix #2500

[{"sha":"d58444be24891127ee53be3ddbf288fd6ac0a34f","author":{"name":"Ben Barsdell","email":"fb55efc015c19b6b983311e9fae7c0ecda2e4774@nvidia.com"},"message":"Use new GPU kernel for [unsorted] segment reductions

- Optionally replaces the old atomics-based kernels with calls to
  SegmentReduceGPU (the same kernel already used for sparse segment
  reductions). This behavior is enabled by default, but the old kernels
  can be re-enabled by setting the environment variable
  TF_USE_ATOMIC_SEGMENT_REDUCTIONS=1. On Windows, the old kernels are
  always used due to a build issue with the new kernel.
- This improves performance, and guarantees that these ops are
  deterministic. In future it is hoped that the old kernels can be
  removed completely.
- Also adds a GPU kernel registration for SegmentMean, which didn't

* Our (IREE) users have been complaining about build issues related to mlir-hlo, so after trying a couple of point fixes, I went a bit deeper.
* Switches the internal CI to BUILD_SHARED_LIBS because that exposes more layering issues.
* Clean up the frightening number of issues exposed.
* Fix the lit/tests setup that I can't figure out why it was working before.
* Other misc fixes to project setup that were exposed.
* Trims down what gets built in LLVM to just what is needed.
* There are *many* more problems in this project but in order to not boil the ocean, I just fixed the things that were immediately exposed.
* I'm breaking the CI changes to another patch because they run afoul of the TypeID issues again (https://llvm.discourse.group/t/checking-types-between-different-python-extensions/3782/34?u=stellaraccident).

Signed-off-by: Charly Molter <charly.molter@konghq.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/686935a133fe521dc325f39419cc32a11f11c882"},{"sha":"d22deab9f9beb7dfafb2ec332478bd1b53d78d6f","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@gmail.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp): Sort services by name when selecting them (#2505)

The default sort in k8s is by CreationTimestamp.
In the case of a deployment created in 2 different k8s clusters if
the services were not created in the same order the inbounds would be
generated in a different order which was confusing to the user.

This commit is part of NETBEANS-5673, which modernizes the look of NetBeans'
window system tabs on the Windows LAF, and makes the tabs look good on various
HiDPI resolutions. I decided to use the FlatLAF tab displayer implementations as
a starting point for the new look rather than the old Windows LAF
implementations, as FlatLAF already handles HiDPI scaling, and has convenient
configuration settings.

This commit does a "clean" copy of a few files from the o.n.swing.laf.flatlaf
module to the o.n.swing.tabcontrol module, only doing as much refactoring as
necessary to avoid dependencies on the actual external FlatLAF library and its
configuration files. Configuration constants are added to Windows8LFCustoms,
initially matching those of FlatLAF Light. In the next commits, I will customize
the configuration and tab displayer implementations to actually look like
Windows 10 style tabs.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nicolaken/netbeans/commits/6a85a4dde678e5b91b983871cfb81ac31759aa57"},{"sha":"684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Various improvements to Windows LAF tab painting logic; part of NETBEANS-5673.

This commit contains various improvements to the tab painting classes that were
copied to the Windows LAF from FlatLAF in the previous commit. These particular
changes may later be ported back to FlatLAF if desired. In this commit, we do
not yet change the actual styling of the tabs.

Details:
* Align and connect borders between tabs and the container panel below,
  including on fractional HiDPI scalings (e.g. 150%). Some visual artifacts
  still exist, e.g. on 125% scaling, but they are less common, and not very
  visible.
* Improve the behavior of DPIUnscaledBorder in more cases.
* Add new configuration options to the TabDisplayerUI classes, to prepare for
  the new tab style on Windows, but do not yet make use of them. This includes
  the ability to draw a border around the selected tab, the ability to set a
  separate hover color for unselected tabs, and support for a color gradient in
  the selected editor tab.
* In editor tabs, avoid showing a tab separator after the last tab.
* In editor tabs, properly handle clipped tabs.
* In view tabs, properly allocate space for the animated "busy" icon.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nicolaken/netbeans/commits/684368f42bc4399d71b2d7ca6c872e3907f017f0"},{"sha":"df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Replace the bitmap 'busy' icon with a manually drawn spinner that scales well on HiDPI/Retina screens.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nicolaken/netbeans/commits/df0cada60669664507d0266314d7b76728d92308"},{"sha":"ad7eea77d996624caf520aa32cfced8250848882","author":{"name":"Eirik Bakke","email":"ddeb4d9fbbe24684d42173e2d1bd3773f25d1719@ultorg.com"},"message":"Adjust some borders on the Windows LAF, and other smaller tweaks.

## Summary

This commit fixes an issue where DevTools would currently not correctly extract the hook names for a hook call when the hook call was nested under *another* hook call, e.g.:

```javascript
function Component() {
  const InnerComponent = useMemo(() => () => {
    const [state, setState] = useState(0);

    return state;
  }); 
  return null;
};
```

Although it seems pretty rare to encounter this case in actual product code, DevTools wasn't handling it correctly:

**Expected Names:**
- `InnerComponent` for the `useMemo()` call.
- `state` for the `useState()` call.

**Actual**
- `InnerComponent` for the `useMemo()` call.
- `InnerComponent` for the `useState()` call.

The reason that we were extracting the name for the nested hook call incorrectly is that the `checkNodeLocation` function (which attempts to check if the location of the hook matches the location in the original source code), was too "lenient" and would return a match even if the start lines of the locations didn't match.

Specifically, for our example, it would consider that the location of the outer hook call "matched" the location of the inner hook call (even though they were on different lines), and would then return the wrong hook name.


### Fix

The fix in this commit is to update the `checkNodeLocation` function to more strictly check for matching start lines. The assumption here is that if 2 locations are on different starting lines, they can't possibly correspond to the same hook call.

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20"},{"sha":"e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Run buildifier","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635"},{"sha":"109d8fb0cd2972cb07fadc772ad9deaf24ae61da","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #48024 from hakos:cpu_feature_guard_lib

PiperOrigin-RevId: 389733406
Change-Id: I10eb0c24b178ba70c6b05f96b923bbe21b9bbe1b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/765ec018a017e16c9e56311be2518d580bb13d06"},{"sha":"d90eab6fcea6738e2909ea2e5b7abc119fe6711a","author":{"name":"Tom Hennigan","email":"31b31641eebbee0b3e16a519fc95fcfec3ff2653@google.com"},"message":"Add TF_ENABLED_DEVICE_TYPES env variable to control which devices TF enables.

Many JAX users make heavy use of TensorFlow on CPU for tasks such as data
loading, processing, saved model etc. These users will use JAX to run programs
on GPU/TPU.

GPU users have reported running near the limit of GPU memory, and we have
tracked this down to them unknowingly running some operations on GPU with TF,
and TF allocating a significant chunk of GPU memory on top of JAX's chunk. This
happens particularly often in TF2 (some statements (e.g. `tfds.load(..)`)
eagerly create TF constants placed on the GPU, users struggle to identify this
code as being responsible for using TF on GPU).

It would be convenient if there was an environment variable we could set to
force all usages of TF in a given program to be CPU only. This is similar in
spirit to variables such as CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES. It would be easy for training
framework developers to deploy for all of their users (e.g. in the same way we
set some sensible defaults for NCCL to improve performance). Given this CL we
can implement this by setting `TF_ENABLED_DEVICE_TYPES=CPU`.

Signed-off-by: Kostadin Plachkov <k.n.plachkov@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/upenderadepu/moby/commits/cd40eb89aea1d5f4fdfe0b0baa5b37ac513f5f75"},{"sha":"0d9b0ed678e2b106e769e974f13aaf100e46351c","author":{"name":"Drew Erny","email":"db55f14336294d3287c922ab67a84bd4af5a0c81@mirantis.com"},"message":"Fix possible overlapping IPs

A node is no longer using its load balancer IP address when it no longer
has tasks that use the network that requires that load balancer. When
this occurs, the swarmkit manager will free that IP in IPAM, and may
reaassign it.

When a task shuts down cleanly, it attempts removal of the networks it
uses, and if it is the last task using those networks, this removal
succeeds, and the load balancer IP is freed.

However, this behavior is absent if the container fails. Removal of the
networks is never attempted.

To address this issue, I amend the executor. Whenever a node load
balancer IP is removed or changed, that information is passedd to the
executor by way of the Configure method. By keeping track of the set of
node NetworkAttachments from the previous call to Configure, we can
determine which, if any, have been removed or changed.

At first, this seems to create a race, by which a task can be attempting
to start and the network is removed right out from under it. However,
this is already addressed in the controller. The controller will attempt
to recreate missing networks before starting a task.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/upenderadepu/moby/commits/1f398f06aa4c533d933bb7335bd9f5047673d7c6"},{"sha":"c7b1e5ba3829a1690a732c19c20d5bf48d58b0d2","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"portallocator: log instead of discard port-range failures

Both getDynamicPortRange() and sanitizePortRange() could produce
and error, and the error message was currently discarded, silently
falling back to using the default port range.

This patch:

- Moves the fallback message from getDynamicPortRange() to getDefaultPortRange(),
  which is where the actual fallback occurs.
- Logs the fallback message and the error that causes the fallback.

The message/error is currently printed at the INFO level, but could be raised
to a WARN, depending on what kind of situations can cause the error.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/upenderadepu/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

[{"sha":"d90eab6fcea6738e2909ea2e5b7abc119fe6711a","author":{"name":"Tom Hennigan","email":"31b31641eebbee0b3e16a519fc95fcfec3ff2653@google.com"},"message":"Add TF_ENABLED_DEVICE_TYPES env variable to control which devices TF enables.

Many JAX users make heavy use of TensorFlow on CPU for tasks such as data
loading, processing, saved model etc. These users will use JAX to run programs
on GPU/TPU.

GPU users have reported running near the limit of GPU memory, and we have
tracked this down to them unknowingly running some operations on GPU with TF,
and TF allocating a significant chunk of GPU memory on top of JAX's chunk. This
happens particularly often in TF2 (some statements (e.g. `tfds.load(..)`)
eagerly create TF constants placed on the GPU, users struggle to identify this
code as being responsible for using TF on GPU).

It would be convenient if there was an environment variable we could set to
force all usages of TF in a given program to be CPU only. This is similar in
spirit to variables such as CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES. It would be easy for training
framework developers to deploy for all of their users (e.g. in the same way we
set some sensible defaults for NCCL to improve performance). Given this CL we
can implement this by setting `TF_ENABLED_DEVICE_TYPES=CPU`.

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20"},{"sha":"e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Run buildifier","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635"},{"sha":"109d8fb0cd2972cb07fadc772ad9deaf24ae61da","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #48024 from hakos:cpu_feature_guard_lib
